Good Morning. The police have killed 24 people in the past three weeks in Dandora, Kayole, Mathare and Majengo, local based human rights organisations have said. They include six in Dandora; two in Mowlem; 10 in Mathare North; four in Majengo; and two in Kayole. Here are the stories making headlines in the Star this Thursday morning. The amendments Kenyans want to the Constitution The National Treasury has completed assessing the financial implications of 28 pieces of legislation proposed by various MPs that are at various stages of processing by Parliament. They include constitutional amendments that could require referenda. National Assembly Budget and Appropriations committee chairman and Kikuyu MP Kimani Ichungw’a told the House that Treasury is finalising the remaining 20 before the report is formally tabled in Parliament. Of the 28 laws, at least six seek to amend the 2010 Constitution and would require a referendum ahead of the 2022 general elections. _____________________________________________________ Assemblies' Speakers want their impeachment decided by Senate The County Assembly Forum now wants enhanced protection to county speakers and their impeachment process amended to the threshold of governors. Intergovernmental Legal Committee chairman Joshua Kiptoo yesterday told senators that the current law where speakers can be impeached within hours is disastrous to the war on corruption at the counties. He claimed that Assemblies’ Speakers have resorted to playing safe at the expense of steering the house to oversight the Executive for fear of being impeached. _____________________________________________________ Kenya, China to sign MoU ending trading imbalance Kenya and China are today expected to sign a Memorandum of Understanding with a view to ending the trade inequalities. President Uhuru Kenyatta and his Chinese counterpart Xi Jinping will preside over the signing of the cooperation agreement. The deal will factor imports and exports of animal and plant products to be traded between the two nations. _____________________________________________________ How Nairobi swindled billions - audit report Auditor General Edward Ouko has revealed massive theft and plunder at the Nairobi county amounting to billions of shilling in unaccounted funds. The 2016-17 report was tabled yesterday by Senate Majority leader Kipchumba Murkomen. Ouko pointed to a porous revenue collection system at City Hall, where only 22 per cent of the revenue collected made it to the bank. The rest was allegedly spent at the source. _____________________________________________________ Why air pollution is a threat to universal health coverage target Air pollution could reverse efforts aimed at enhancing universal health coverage in the country. The World Health Organisation says around 3 billion people globally cook using polluting open fires or simple stoves fuelled by kerosene, biomass (wood, animal dung and crop waste) and coal. The global body says that close to 4 million people die prematurely every year from illness attributable to household air pollution. _____________________________________________________ For more on these stories and others, keep browsing the Star website for the latest news making headlines across Kenya and around the world. To get the Breakfast Briefing right into your inbox every morning, click here for a free subscription. Click here for the latest political news